Title: Definition of x86 Architecture
Content: The x86 architecture is a widely used computer processor architecture.

Title: Origin of the Name
Content: Name comes from early Intel processors.

Title: Common Identifier
Content: "86" became the common identifier of this series.

Title: Backward Compatibility
Content: New x86 processors can run software designed for older processors.

Title: Widely Supported
Content: Almost all operating systems and software support x86 architecture.

Title: Hardware and Software Support
Content: Extensive hardware and software support: There are a large number of hardware and software tools designed for the x86 architecture on the market, ensuring a good ecosystem and user support.

Title: Complex Instruction Set
Content: Complex instruction set: x86 is a complex instruction set computer (CISC) whose instruction set contains a large number of instructions and features designed to complete complex tasks through a single instruction to reduce program code length and improve efficiency.

Title: High-Speed Storage Locations
Content: Registers are high-speed storage locations directly inside the CPU.

Title: Intel Program Execution Registers
Content: Intel basic program execution registers include several types.

Title: 32-bit General-Purpose Registers
Content: Registers include EFLAGS, EIP, EBX, ECX, EDX, EBP, ESP, ESI, EDI.

Title: EFLAGS Usage
Content: EFLAGS is used for processor status flag.

Title: EIP Function
Content: EIP acts as the instruction pointer.

Title: 16-bit Segment Registers
Content: Includes cs, ss, DS, ES, FS, GS.
